In this press briefing, White House Press Secretary Jay Carney discusses various topics, including the House Republican vote on rejecting a debt limit increase, President Karzai's opposition to NATO air strikes in Afghanistan, the housing market, and the nomination of John Bryson for Commerce Secretary. Carney emphasizes the importance of deficit reduction and raising the debt ceiling, and expresses confidence that both will happen. He also addresses concerns about the economy, consumer confidence, and the impact of budget cuts on the middle class. However, he does not provide specific timelines for when the economy will improve or when people will see relief. Regarding the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Carney does not comment on specific legislation but reiterates the administration's commitment to working with Congress on economic growth and job creation. He also deflects questions about the involvement of the White House in the Tucson memorial slogan and the President's stance on gay marriage.